00:08.760 --> 00:12.660
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.380 --> 00:33.720
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:36.380 --> 00:38.080
And here are your hosts.

00:42.660 --> 00:50.540
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. Harry Harrison is one of the pioneers of
adventure science fiction. His Deathworld trilogy, written in the 1960s, is a

00:50.540 --> 00:58.500
prime example. Recently, Harrison completed another adventure series entitled To
the Stars, a trilogy comprising Homeworld, Wheelworld, and Starworld. In

00:58.500 --> 01:05.800
Homeworld, we find a 500-year distant Britain under the heels of a strong
government. In Wheelworld, we find a planet whose harsh conditions are

01:05.800 --> 01:13.280
reminiscent of earlier Harrison novels. In the final novel, Starworld, we find
America 500 years from now. As it turns out, Harrison wrote the middle

01:13.280 --> 01:24.180
installment, Wheelworld, first. The trilogy came about through the inability I
have just to take the situation as set. I know where I got the idea from when I

01:24.180 --> 01:30.380
was in California on the freeway with my friend Brian Aldis. We were in a
horrible little English Sprite, which is just about 8 inches high and 2 feet

01:30.380 --> 01:40.860
wide. It goes a maximum of 50 miles an hour. And we're trundling along five-lane
freeway, California 5. Great big articulated trucks with trails going by with 14

01:40.860 --> 01:48.120
-foot high wheels. I'm looking at the bottom of hubcaps, you know, trying to
keep this thing going straight. God, I had a vision at that point of a world

01:48.120 --> 01:57.560
where trucks ran forever, on and on and on, around the whole planet. How do we
do that? So I had to develop a whole planet and a culture to get them there. And

01:57.560 --> 02:03.880
by the time I'd done it and written the book, the editor said, I feel it's
incomplete. How did I get there in the first place? And what happened to that

02:03.880 --> 02:10.200
revolution afterwards? And I said, you're right. I've got so much plotting in
here. I have a whole book before and a book afterwards. So I took the character.

02:10.280 --> 02:18.160
He'd ride this planet for nameless reasons. And it ended up with a revolution,
which was going wrong. So I went back and told you how he got there, which took

02:18.160 --> 02:25.260
an earth. And I closed the book together in the final one. They came out
different. The one middle one was written first. They had to be different

02:25.260 --> 02:32.320
aspects, you know. Then the third one, of course, put the first two together.
Harrison was able to assemble a number of his plot devices in this series. And

02:32.320 --> 02:40.780
there was a message, as is usual, for Harrison. I used different things at
different times in there. High technology and enjoyment of technology and a

02:40.780 --> 02:48.500
little bit of politics. And the first one in some ways is like make room, make
room. It's where we're going to go if we don't get a hold of technology and what

02:48.500 --> 03:00.080
we can do. If you notice, the first book shows you how rotten Britain will be
500 years from now. The third book, how rotten America will be 500 years from

03:00.080 --> 03:09.380
now. And all done through good intentions with lack of knowledge of how to go
about taking care or helping people. And they're both rotten worlds. So there

03:09.380 --> 03:18.360
again, the admonitory thing is being shaken. No, you must get technologies
involved. You must do somehow, not guess, you must just somehow do a better job

03:18.360 --> 03:27.620
of ruling the world, you know. We're in a technological world and nobody in the
British Parliament or the American Senate or legislation knows anything about

03:27.620 --> 03:37.480
science. I mean, we, a bunch of ex-lawyers and politicians. Politicians have
one, one motivation in life, that's to get re-elected. Look at the whole Nixon

03:37.480 --> 03:43.900
trouble came about because all he wanted to do was be re-elected and doesn't
care what you do. And that's the wrong thing. I'm not saying, I can't see any

03:43.900 --> 03:50.480
easy answers to it. I'm just saying that there are answers. We are now at
technological evolution. We now are going into the computer world. And no one

03:50.480 --> 03:58.640
has consistently thought what will happen to most people. And in a way, behind
all the adventure stories there is a consideration of those problems. Harrison

03:58.640 --> 04:10.180
told us that the grim future depicted in the To the Stars trilogy has its roots
in Orwell's 1984. The first book, plot-wise and character-wise, is a tip of the

04:10.180 --> 04:18.960
hat, a nod of the head, to George Orwell's 1984. I even used the word pints,
leaders for pint in there, his thing, they were drinking leaders instead of

04:18.960 --> 04:33.000
pints. I used the word prose. I put the clues in there for you to find. And the
brother-in-law character is the same torturer character from Brian O'Brien. O

04:33.000 --> 04:42.560
'Brien was the other fellow. It is the man who knows he's evil and is in charge
of an evil society. And that's why he's in the first book. But having not killed

04:42.560 --> 04:50.320
him off in the first, he has to appear again. And then you get what I thought
was the only truthful ending, an ambiguous ending to the third one. People hate

04:50.320 --> 04:58.900
me for it. What happened? I said, that's what life is. Fiction gives you easy
answers, but in real life there are no easy answers, you know. We'll have more

04:58.900 --> 05:00.240
with Harry Harrison on our next show.

05:07.620 --> 05:15.560
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
