06:07.660 --> 06:11.640
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:27.320 --> 06:32.640
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:35.320 --> 06:37.020
And here are your hosts.

06:41.840 --> 06:49.900
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. Science fiction author Harry Harrison writes
many styles of science fiction. One of these is adventure science fiction. Here

06:49.900 --> 06:58.340
he tells us how he came to write Planet of No Return, the sequel to an earlier
effort, Planet of the Damned. The exorcist of publishing produced strange

06:58.340 --> 07:09.020
offspring. I wrote Planet of the Damned years ago. In a way, it's Deathworld
one more time, with slight differences. I wrote Deathworld five or six times,

07:09.040 --> 07:19.100
one guy to another, until I decided to break out and do build a galactic hero.
And I did that. It was completely into itself. And then a few years ago, a

07:19.100 --> 07:26.660
publisher was doing these illustrated books, which really are just juveniles.
That's what they are. They're really short novels with pictures in them for

07:26.660 --> 07:35.100
kids. And unlike most science fiction writers, I ran out of money at the time.
And he said, Harry, are you doing illustrated books for me? I said, no. He said,

07:35.100 --> 07:44.880
we'll give you an X number of $1,000. And I said, yes. And I shopped around my
older books. And so I could do a sequel, a fast-paced adventure book, with a

07:44.880 --> 07:52.120
little content as well. A little bit about women's rights in there, if you look
closely at the end. You know, they're all male fascist swine, these guys. They

07:52.120 --> 07:59.760
love to kill each other. And a little bit of plot, mystery plot. An option for a
film to make a nice, fast film. You know, it was not a bad book. It's a

07:59.760 --> 08:07.480
juvenile, done for a certain market. Not ashamed of it or proud of it. Just a
book I did, and there it is. Humor is another Harrison trademark. The

08:07.480 --> 08:16.760
Technicolor Time Machine is a vintage Harrison humor novel. Yet when he began
it, Harrison intended for it to be quite serious. In The Technicolor Time

08:16.760 --> 08:27.080
Machine, I implied this is a very, very serious book. Time travel. And when I
got this paparazzo Italian camera and back facing this great big nine-foot-tall

08:27.080 --> 08:35.060
Viking, I started to laugh. And it came out funny. But if you look, there's a
very solid time travel plot, which could be a serious book. Except I started

08:35.060 --> 08:41.920
laughing. And I'm laughing. Why shouldn't the readers laugh? And the way the
thing went, it took off that way. And I think it had that serious structure

08:41.920 --> 08:49.860
beneath it. But Star Smashers of the Galaxy Rangers, on the other hand, was
intended to be funny from the start. A Star Smashers of the Galaxy Rangers was

08:49.860 --> 09:01.280
just, I was feeling a deadly mood one day, and I was so tired of rubbish. I was
so tired of, you know, dear old Doc Smith wrote his space operas back in the 30s

09:01.280 --> 09:10.660
and 40s. That's a long time ago. And it's a period form of art I think is dead.
But I keep seeing certain writers who shall be nameless rehashing old space

09:10.660 --> 09:20.040
operas. I said, oh, I had enough of this. So I said, why not just put the boot
to all the space operas at one time, have fun doing it. And I made internal

09:20.040 --> 09:26.580
parodies of everyone I could think of. People accuse me of hating Doc Smith. I
say, no, I don't like it. I love Doc Smith. I grew up reading Doc Smith. But I

09:26.580 --> 09:32.880
just don't, I think I feel it's dead. I'd like to put a tombstone over it. Not
that you ever can in fiction. They're still going on doing it anyway. But I

09:32.880 --> 09:40.340
enjoy myself. The readers enjoy it. Some, I mean, the two kind of readers. Some
say, you're hating Doc Smith. You know, they chase me around. Others say, oh, I

09:40.340 --> 09:49.840
feel a chair. You know, so there it is. It takes your choice. One of Harrison's
latest novels is actually science fiction, but it's being marketed as a

09:49.840 --> 10:01.760
mainstream book. Rebel in Time was a definite attempt to, between myself and the
publisher, I had the idea. I saw the idea as being something that a non-science

10:01.760 --> 10:11.760
fiction reader would buy. Science fiction sells 20% of all fiction in the United
States in paperback, which is not bad. But being a writer, I see 80% more I

10:11.760 --> 10:19.860
could sell. And publishers like to sell more, too. So we talked about the novel.
I said it's pure science fiction, but it starts out as a mystery novel. And it's

10:19.860 --> 10:26.620
a good quarter of the way into it before the science fiction element is brought
in. And it's a science fiction element that the reader will accept, any general

10:26.620 --> 10:34.180
reader. And by that time, he's trapped. 10, 20 years ago, I couldn't have done
that because I had no big name. And then the readers would not have bought it.

10:35.620 --> 10:41.760
Now, I have enough readers around. They'll see it, my name on it. They'll look
at it, open it, maybe buy it. The science fiction readers. So I don't think

10:41.760 --> 10:48.360
we'll lose one science fiction reader by packaging it that way. We might pick up
a lot of other readers, which would make me happy, my publisher happy, my wife

10:48.360 --> 10:55.280
happy, my children, my bank manager. You know, all the things we want to make
happy. We'll talk with Harry Harrison about short stories on our next show.

11:02.600 --> 11:10.440
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

11:10.440 --> 11:11.200
Odessa, Texas.

12:00.380 --> 12:04.300
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

12:19.980 --> 12:25.360
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

12:27.980 --> 12:29.740
And here are your hosts.

12:34.100 --> 12:41.020
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Although science fiction author Harry
Harrison is noted for his many fine novels, he's an accomplished short story

12:41.020 --> 12:49.300
writer as well. He gave us some thoughts on short stories. In science fiction,
unlike a lot of other fiction, there are people who write both short stories and

12:49.300 --> 13:01.160
novels. Some of them can, but a lot of them can. And very simply, it is least
residual. A short story is a one-idea story. A single gimmick or device, a turn

13:01.160 --> 13:09.920
of plot, and you write that to length and stop it at two or three or four or
five thousand words. If it's complicated, it goes to ten thousand novelettes. As

13:09.920 --> 13:21.120
opposed to a novel, which is a complex thought that requires modifications, more
than one idea, ramifications, and then it goes to novel length. And many times I

13:21.120 --> 13:27.920
first started writing, I had these short story ideas. And they're very good to
do. They go in the magazines, they go in anthologies, readers recognize your

13:27.920 --> 13:36.180
name. And deliberately, between novels, we do a half dozen short stories.
Unhappily, after a number of years of writing, you find publishers want to give

13:36.180 --> 13:47.080
you more money for novels. And they really do, the word rate per word in a novel
is about ten times a short story. And I find myself tending to cook one novel at

13:47.080 --> 13:53.460
the end of the other. I've written a short story in three or four or five years,
which I think is a shame, because I have four collections of short stories out,

13:53.460 --> 14:01.880
all selling quite nicely, and they've anthologized in about 22 languages. One of
Harrison's best-known short stories is Rescue Operation. It tells about an alien

14:01.880 --> 14:09.580
that crash lands in Yugoslavia and of the alien's fate in the hands of an
ignorant, superstitious priest. Harrison's travels in Yugoslavia inspired this

14:09.580 --> 14:18.760
story. Rescue Operation came out, everything in there I know except the alien.
In Yugoslavia, the most broken-down country in Western Europe, they have

14:18.760 --> 14:29.440
peasants there, which are much more broken down than German peasants. They have
deeply religious, simple-mindedly stupid, people-burning peasants within ten

14:29.440 --> 14:38.580
miles of a nuclear reactor. The perfect analog of our world. Instead of northern
civilized countries, southern poor, uncivilized countries, all in one country.

14:39.900 --> 14:47.120
And having been in the middle of this and having had a number of desperately
awful things happen to me and my family down there, the children got scarlet

14:47.120 --> 14:56.940
fever, had injections with blunt needles, had to carry them screaming, you know,
sort of thing. And living in that desperate, awful world, and there again, the

14:56.940 --> 15:06.180
background was there. And then the thought, instead of arriving in Central Park
in front of the White House, what if the alien from space arrived there? Voila,

15:06.420 --> 15:08.680
you know, complete. Just a matter of writing it.

15:17.540 --> 15:25.680
Another well-known Harrison short story is Mute Milton, the story of a black man
whose bus stops in a small southern town a few years ago. This moving, gut

15:25.680 --> 15:33.340
-wrenching story was inspired by an incident in Harrison's life. Harrison's
anger, which comes across clearly in the story, was genuine. Living in

15:33.340 --> 15:42.920
Scandinavia, been out of the States two or three or four years, and the Danes
are absolutely colorblind. That, in fact, in those days, really, certain kind of

15:42.920 --> 15:48.860
girls only date black men. Other girls used to look down upon them. There were
about four black men in the whole country, you know. And, you know, it's very

15:48.860 --> 15:57.600
easy to be pro-race, anti-racial, if you're in a country with no race problems.
But living there, children growing up there, and Martin Luther King was shot,

15:57.800 --> 16:06.160
and a newspaper called me and asked me my opinion on it, you know, and they were
all horrified. And then I picked a copy of Newsweek up, and they had some great

16:06.160 --> 16:15.420
big-bellied Alabama. I photographed him with a shotgun in one hand, a nose
-picker in the other, and his belly hanging over his belt, you know, saying,

16:15.520 --> 16:23.480
well, just one more nigga to me. And I just, my white heat engulfed my mind. You
know, one of America's, he got the Nobel Prize a little earlier than that. You

16:23.480 --> 16:30.160
know, one of America's, well, I was very proud when he came over there. I was in
Scandinavia, hit an American getting a prize for doing something really good in

16:30.160 --> 16:41.280
the world, being honored for it. And I saw red, and the idea came to me, you
know, the story just began to put into a story that rage I had, that strong

16:41.280 --> 16:44.740
feeling. And if a writer can do that, well, then you're a successful story.

