18:09.820 --> 18:15.140
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

18:17.800 --> 18:19.460
And here are your hosts.

18:23.500 --> 18:27.460
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane, A regional science fiction anthology:

18:27.680 --> 18:33.140
what in the world is that? Well, it's a collection of
science fiction stories written by folks from a particular area of the country.

18:33.340 --> 18:40.540
Ah, you mean like New York, where science fiction really started, or like
California, where all the writers live? Well, yes, but try Texas, because that's

18:40.540 --> 18:47.180
where the first one came out. The first regional science fiction anthology was
Lone Star Universe, and it was billed as speculative fiction and fantasy by

18:47.180 --> 18:56.660
Texans. Oh, that's the book edited by George Proctor and Stephen Utley that came
out in 1976. It's that collection of 17 short stories written by Texans. Right.

18:56.880 --> 19:06.280
We got to talk to George Proctor, and we asked him how the book came about.
Well, one day, a bunch of us who had just made their first sales were sitting

19:06.280 --> 19:13.760
around laughingly, saying, yeah, one day there's going to be enough writers in
Texas that we can put out our own anthology, and to hell with all these people

19:13.760 --> 19:23.820
that will buy our stories. And as it was, I think that was Howard Waldrop was
there, Stephen Utley, Buddy Saunders, and we're just sitting around joking,

19:24.020 --> 19:25.080
putting a fanzine together.

19:28.000 --> 19:31.000
And I guess I was the only person that really sort of took it seriously.

19:34.180 --> 19:45.840
And as it was, Steve and I put a proposal together and sent it first to a man
out in Midland, Odessa, whose name escapes me now, but he was doing Texana-type

19:45.840 --> 19:58.340
books. And he came back and liked the idea but wasn't going to pick it up and
suggested we send it to Heidelberg Press in Austin. And we did, and they picked

19:58.340 --> 20:08.860
it up. And by that time, there were enough known writers in Texas and award
winners that it really did seem feasible and seemed like a good idea.

20:12.500 --> 20:25.560
And it got put together. Sort of interesting. It makes for a lot of jokes, you
know, regional science fiction. But our thought was, you know, Texana's in, and

20:25.560 --> 20:36.400
here's this whole realm that's never been really looked at. And what's funny is
it sparked a lot of other regional science fiction books. It was the first. And

20:36.400 --> 20:47.320
everybody chuckled and laughed. And then there was about five that came out on
its heels because it had never been thought of. And what was funny is that I

20:47.320 --> 20:59.700
meet new editors in New York. They know my name, The Lone Star Universe, rather
than some of the novels I've done, which is surprising. But again, New York is

20:59.700 --> 21:03.640
surprised by new ideas. And that's, I think, the reason it was noticed.

21:14.540 --> 21:22.620
Hey, I know a lot about science fiction, and I have this vast collection of
science fiction books. Well, maybe it's only half vast. But anyway, I've never

21:22.620 --> 21:29.360
seen a copy of The Lone Star Universe, let alone heard of it. What gives?
There's a good reason for that. Proctor told us that the book received only

21:29.360 --> 21:40.260
limited distribution. Heidelberg stopped publishing, as best I can tell, just
about the time they brought out the book. There were big plans to do posters and

21:40.260 --> 21:50.460
everything to go with the book. You know, full posters of the cover, which the
cover is gorgeous. It's one of those double-take covers. And as it was, they

21:50.460 --> 21:59.060
sort of went out of business about that time. And as far as I know, only a few
thousand were distributed, and they're still sitting in a warehouse somewhere,

21:59.660 --> 22:02.260
making scarce items.

22:04.420 --> 22:14.060
It's surprising that you go to conventions, large conventions in and out of
state, and there will always be several people asking me how you get a copy of

22:14.060 --> 22:23.720
the book. It's rare because it was not distributed. And there's apparently tons
of the books still around. You just can't get a hold of them. It's a nice item

22:23.720 --> 22:31.440
to have for a collector. Well, you can bet I'm going to be on the lookout for
that book. In the meantime, we'll have more about Lone Star Universe on our next

22:31.440 --> 22:31.740
show.

22:39.220 --> 22:47.000
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

22:47.000 --> 22:47.740
Odessa, Texas.

23:38.080 --> 23:42.020
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

23:57.820 --> 24:03.140
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

24:05.840 --> 24:07.480
And here are your hosts.

24:11.400 --> 24:19.400
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. Last time we talked about Lone Star
Universe, the first regional science fiction anthology. Edited by George Proctor

24:19.400 --> 24:26.640
and Stephen Utley, Lone Star Universe is a collection of short stories written
by Texans. The anthology is a sought-after collector's item. It's not readily

24:26.640 --> 24:33.660
available because it was poorly distributed when it was published in 1976. We
talked with one of the editors, George Proctor, and we asked him if the book

24:33.660 --> 24:45.380
might someday be reprinted, perhaps as a paperback. I don't think so, because I
think it's a limited item to Texana. I really think it has more value as Texana

24:45.380 --> 24:52.200
than it does to the science fiction field as a whole. Those science fiction
collectors want it because it is a first.

24:56.400 --> 25:06.680
The stories are good. I think there's a wide variety of stories. Science fiction
reviews that I saw of it, their complaint was that there was a wide variety of

25:06.680 --> 25:18.740
stories in there, that it wasn't all nuts and bolts, and it wasn't all new way,
but there was everything. And that's, the whole idea of the book was to show the

25:18.740 --> 25:28.980
diversity of the science fiction writers in this state. I think it did that
well. I think it produced good stories by everybody that was in there. Proctor

25:28.980 --> 25:32.560
told us that editing a second volume of Lone Star Universe is not out of the
question.

25:35.240 --> 25:52.840
There may or may not be. It depends on, you know, I know of one person now who
is editor for a Texas publisher, and he has mentioned in passing that he'd like

25:52.840 --> 26:04.620
to get a hold of the first book, since it never was really distributed, is maybe
buy them all out if possible. Whether or not that will ever happen is something

26:04.620 --> 26:14.280
else, but yeah, why not? It was fun. The people who got it seemed to enjoy it,
and I still think if it would get some sort of distribution, it would be a money

26:14.280 --> 26:15.980
-making book in Texas.

26:18.900 --> 26:23.080
Just the charisma

26:23.080 --> 26:41.840
of the state and the chauvinistic attitude of Texans, which is equivalent to New
York, we're just larger. We buy Texana. Whether we read it or not, we buy it,

26:41.840 --> 26:44.800
and I think there's a market for it.

26:52.540 --> 27:00.100
So Proctor feels that Lone Star Universe might be more in demand as a
collector's item for collectors of Texana than as reading material for science

27:00.100 --> 27:09.880
fiction readers. We ask him why Texas seems to be spawning so many new science
fiction writers. They've always been around. They've never been noted as Texan

27:09.880 --> 27:24.700
before. I think early 70s to mid-70s, we had a lot of fans who turned
professional, started selling their stories. They were friends from all over the

27:24.700 --> 27:31.740
state. They suddenly became a very large group that were selling and were
noticeable.

27:34.840 --> 27:46.900
That this group was here, had made it, gave a lot of other folks who wanted to
write incentive to do it. And you've got suddenly a whole second wave of Texas

27:46.900 --> 27:56.000
writers coming out, meeting them here for the first time, that have just begun
to sell their first stories or their first novel, but you've suddenly got a

27:56.000 --> 28:03.280
second wave of Texas science fiction writers, which is kind of nice. Texas
writers have been rearing their heads recently, and Lone Star Universe is an

28:03.280 --> 28:10.580
excellent anthology of their work. Other regions are producing a lot of science
fiction these days, notably Oregon, Florida, upstate New York, and New Orleans.

28:10.980 --> 28:15.860
But it was the Texans, with their bigger-than-life state and their pride, who
produced the first regional anthology.

